Datasets.
For a comprehensive comparison, we evaluate FedGTA and other baselines under both transductive and inductive settings.
For transductive settings, we conduct experiments on 3 small-scale citation networks (Cora, Citeseer, PubMed)Â (Yang
etÂ al., 2016), 2 medium-scale user-item datasets (Amazon Computer, Amazon Photo), 2 medium-scale Coauthor datasets (Coauthor CS, Coauthor Physics)Â (Shchur etÂ al., 2018), and 3 large-scale OGB datasets (ogbn-arxiv, ogbn-products, ogbn-papers100M)Â (Hu etÂ al., 2020).
For inductive settings, we conduct experiments on 2 datasets of medium and large scales: Flickr and RedditÂ (Zeng etÂ al., 2020).
More details about the above datasets can be found in TableÂ 2.
Based on this, we provide LouvainÂ (Blondel etÂ al., 2008) and MetisÂ (Karypis and Kumar, 1998) split, which are widely used in FGLÂ (He etÂ al., 2021; Wang etÂ al., 2022; Zhang
etÂ al., 2021; Baek
etÂ al., 2023).
Specifically, we apply Louvain on the global graph to assign discovered communities to multi-clients.
In the Metis split, we assign nodes to each client based on the given number of clients.
Notably, since the ogbn-papers100M dataset contains a large number of unlabeled nodes, we only perform Louvain split on it.
This is because we can control the amount of labeled data contained by each client by assigning communities.

To answer Q1, we report the transductive performance in TableÂ 3, where FedGTA outperforms other baselines.
Specifically, compared to the second result, FedGTA achieves an average improvement of 2.33% and 2.54% when using GCN and GAMLP.
While FedGL and FedSage+ outperform methods using GCN as the local model in some cases, they cannot achieve more competitive results and even fail to handle large-scale scenarios due to their limited scalability.

To answer Q2, we demonstrate that FedGTA can be applied to a large variety of GNN variants:
GCN, GAMLP, SIGN, S2GC, SGC, GraphSAGE, and GBP are shown in TableÂ 3, TableÂ 4, and TableÂ 6.
Building upon the above backbone GNNs, to test the effectiveness of our proposed FedGTA, we evaluate it on both coupled and sampling-based GNN models, which differ in the orderings of feature propagation and transformation.
Through the above experiments, we observe that FedGTA consistently outperforms the other FGL optimization baselines in both GNN categories.

To answer Q3, we focus on the implementation of FedGTA on the client and server side.
Specifically, we present the ablation experiments shown in TableÂ 6 to investigate the contribution of local smoothing confidence and mixed moments of neighbor features computed on the client side.
Subsequently, their efficacy hinges on the serverâ€™s ability to perform efficient model aggregation, thereby achieving optimized federated training.
The visualization of server-side model aggregation based on our method is presented in Fig.Â 3.

In the ablation study, we use â€Mom.â€ and â€Conf.â€ to represent the mixed moments of neighbor features and local smoothing confidence.
We also use â€SAGEâ€ to refer to the GraphSage model.
According to the experimental results shown in TableÂ 6, we observe that both Mom. and Conf. contribute to the improvement of the optimization process significantly.
Furthermore, the combination of them reduces the variance during the federated training process.
